{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659276"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:09:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:09:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20863"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20863"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.05,0.05,0.1,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97383"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13738"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20863"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79998"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11020"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12317"},{"type":"tags","id":"12684"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33064"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33065"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97383"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents with fever, joint pain, and a butterfly-shaped rash across her cheeks. Laboratory investigations reveal positive antinuclear antibodies and anti-double-stranded DNA antibodies. A kidney biopsy is performed to evaluate her proteinuria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the characteristic histopathological finding in type III hypersensitivity reactions?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cytotoxic T-cell destruction of tissues","Eosinophilic infiltration of tissues","Granulomatous inflammation with giant cells","Antibody-mediated lysis of target cells","Fibrinoid necrosis of vessel walls"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EType III hypersensitivity reactions occur when immune complexes deposit in tissues, triggering complement activation and inflammation. The characteristic finding is \u003Cstrong\u003Efibrinoid necrosis of vessel walls\u003C/strong\u003E, which appears microscopically as smudgy, eosinophilic material in vessel walls accompanied by neutrophilic infiltration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other patterns are characteristic of different hypersensitivity types:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytotoxic T-cell destruction of tissues\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in type IV (cell-mediated) hypersensitivity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic infiltration of tissues\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in type I (IgE-mediated) hypersensitivity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation with giant cells\u003C/strong\u003E develops in type IV hypersensitivity reactions like tuberculosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibody-mediated lysis of target cells\u003C/strong\u003E characterizes type II hypersensitivity where antibodies bind cell surface antigens\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn lupus nephritis, immune complexes deposit along glomerular basement membranes, appearing as granular deposits on immunofluorescence microscopy. This pattern of injury leads to the proteinuria seen in this patient with systemic lupus erythematosus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Type III hypersensitivity reactions are caused by immune complex deposition in tissues, leading to complement activation and inflammation.","The principal morphologic manifestation of immune complex injury is acute vasculitis with fibrinoid necrosis of vessel walls.","In the kidney, immune complexes appear as granular deposits of immunoglobulin and complement on immunofluorescence microscopy."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; page 212."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79998"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20863"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79998"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:31:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:32:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13738"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97383"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11020"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Hypersensitivity reactions","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diseases of the immune system","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":5,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},